  "text": "It may seem paradoxical that post-ischemic mitochondrial dysfunction does not add injury, but confers protection. For several authors, including us, this is the basis of the concept that cardioprotection is afforded by a partial degree of mitochondrial dysfunction which may lead to ROS signaling [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . In fact, when oxygen supply is re-established after a prolonged ischemia, if something (e.g., acidosis, cyclosporin A) prevents prolonged mPTP opening and RIRR, the partial mitochondrial dysfunction may allow ROS signaling.",
